{
  "text": "A critical trigger underlying virtually all forms of synaptic plasticity is related to changes occurring in the concentration of postsynaptic calcium (Ca 2\u03e9 ) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The \"calcium hypothesis\" proposes that a large postsynaptic Ca 2\u03e9 influx favors LTP, whereas moderate increases in postsynaptic Ca 2\u03e9 favor LTD. For example, in the hippocampus, [CITATION_3] showed that brief tetanic stimulation (which normally produced LTP) is able to elicit LTD if NMDA channels were partially blocked by moderate concentrations of D-APV or cells were voltage clamped at hyperpolarized potentials, thereby limiting postsynaptic Ca 2\u03e9 influx. The induction of LTP and LTD in the spinal cord may also depend on the magnitude of evoked increases in Ca 2\u03e9 levels [CITATION_4] ). Since 5-HT did not significantly alter resting membrane potential in our study, we propose that 5-HT is capable of reducing the level of postsynaptic Ca 2\u03e9 influx by depressing voltage-dependent Ca 2\u03e9 channel activity. This in turn causes only moderate increases in Ca 2\u03e9 and hence would tend to induce LTD rather than LTP. There are numerous examples of an inhibition of Ca 2\u03e9 channels by 5-HT 1-like receptors (e.g., Scroggs and Anderson 1990; for review see Anwyl 1990).",
  "citation_candidates": [
